WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:02.340
<v Instructor>So here is an service</v>

2
00:00:02.340 --> 00:00:04.950
that I'm sure you won't forget once I tell you about it.

3
00:00:04.950 --> 00:00:07.950
It's called the AWS Ground Station.

4
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:10.500
So the idea is that this is fully managed service

5
00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:13.590
that lets you control satellites communication,

6
00:00:13.590 --> 00:00:16.380
process data, and scale your satellites operations.

7
00:00:16.380 --> 00:00:18.000
So this is not for everyone,

8
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.970
but you have satellites running around the Earth,

9
00:00:20.970 --> 00:00:23.730
a lot of them, and you may want to get access

10
00:00:23.730 --> 00:00:25.800
to their data for whatever reason.

11
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:27.960
So Ground Station provides you a global network

12
00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.170
of satellite ground stations near AWS regions.

13
00:00:31.170 --> 00:00:33.840
So that it's easier for you to get data

14
00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:37.200
from your satellites onto your AWS cloud.

15
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:38.160
So how does that work?

16
00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:39.900
Well, thanks to the Ground Station service,

17
00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:43.110
you're going to be allowed to download the satellite data

18
00:00:43.110 --> 00:00:45.810
to your AWS VPC within seconds.

19
00:00:45.810 --> 00:00:47.940
So the Ground Station runs within the cloud.

20
00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:49.890
It's connected to satellites,

21
00:00:49.890 --> 00:00:52.650
and then you download data from satellites

22
00:00:52.650 --> 00:00:55.890
to Amazon S3 buckets, or your EC2 instance,

23
00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:59.550
and from that, you can process it the way you want.

24
00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:01.500
So this is something, believe me,

25
00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:05.220
that was hard to do before the AWS Ground Station service,

26
00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:07.950
but now, it is very easy to do.

27
00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:09.510
The use cases for this,

28
00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:11.760
if you have access to satellites of course,

29
00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:14.700
is to do weather forecasting, surface imaging,

30
00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:17.220
communications, or video broadcast.

31
00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:18.600
I hope you liked this lecture,

32
00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:21.200
and I will see you in the stars in the next lecture.

